cards.lyrics:
Luna opens the case on the kitchen table. Inside, the telescope is in pieces — the main lens cracked cleanly in two.

@LUNA
Dad's telescope.
@OSCAR
I know.
@LUNA
Oscar, this is —
@OSCAR
It's a broken telescope, Luna. It's forty years old.
@LUNA
He fixed it every time. Every single time something went wrong with it, he fixed it.
@OSCAR
He's not here.

Silence. Luna picks up one half of the lens and holds it to the light.

@OSCAR
The observatory called. They're closing. Hatch is buying the land.
@LUNA
When?
@OSCAR
Thirty days.
@LUNA
That's not enough time.
@OSCAR
Time for what?

A formal letter on city letterhead sits on the doorstep. Luna reads it aloud.

@LUNA
"...the property located at 14 Observatory Road will transfer to Hatch Development LLC on or before the thirtieth of the month. All occupants must vacate..."

@LUNA
Dr. Vale lives there.
@OSCAR
I know.
@LUNA
She's been there for forty years.
@OSCAR
Luna —
@LUNA
Someone has to do something.
@OSCAR
Someone. Not us.
@LUNA
Then who?

Oscar has no answer.

Luna finds Felix on his front porch, wrapped in a blanket even though it's not cold.

@LUNA
I need your help.
@FELIX
With what.
@LUNA
The observatory.
@FELIX
Absolutely not.
@LUNA
Felix —
@FELIX
It's dark up there, Luna. It's dark and it smells like old paper and there are definitely bats.
@LUNA
There are no bats.
@FELIX
You don't know that.
@LUNA
I need someone to hold the flashlight.
@FELIX
Get a lamp.
@LUNA
Felix. Please.

Felix looks at her for a long moment.

@FELIX
If I see one bat. One bat, Luna.
@LUNA
No bats.
@FELIX
One bat and I'm gone.
@LUNA
Deal.

The observatory interior. Cardboard boxes everywhere. Star charts rolled and rubber-banded. Dr. Vale doesn't look up when they enter.

@DR. VALE
We're closed.
@LUNA
The door was open.
@DR. VALE
The lock is broken. It's been broken for six years. That doesn't mean come in.
@LUNA
I'm Luna Carter. My father used to volunteer here.
@DR. VALE
I remember your father.

A long pause. Dr. Vale sets down her chart.

@DR. VALE
What do you want.
@LUNA
I want to fix the telescope.
@DR. VALE
It's a two-thousand-dollar repair on equipment that will be demolished in thirty days.
@LUNA
Twenty-nine.
@DR. VALE
What?
@LUNA
Twenty-nine days. The letter came yesterday.

Dr. Vale looks at her for the first time.

@DR. VALE
You can read.
@LUNA
I can also hold a flashlight.
@FELIX
(quietly, from behind Luna)
She can. She's very good at it.

Dr. Vale spreads a forty-year star chart across the worktable.

@DR. VALE
I have four thousand, three hundred and twelve hand-drawn charts. Each one needs to be scanned at three hundred DPI and cross-referenced against the university database before the thirtieth.
@LUNA
That's a lot.
@DR. VALE
Yes.
@LUNA
Could we do it?
@DR. VALE
I don't know. Could you?
@LUNA
If you teach me how the scanner works.
@DR. VALE
It's not complicated.
@LUNA
Then yes. I think we could.

Dr. Vale considers this.

@DR. VALE
I'll teach you the scanner. You fix the telescope.
@LUNA
Deal.
@DR. VALE
I don't shake hands.
@LUNA
That's okay.
@DR. VALE
Good.

Town Hall. The whole room is watching. Oscar stands at the microphone.

@OSCAR
I support the proposal.

Murmurs from the crowd. Luna stares at him from the third row.

@OSCAR
The observatory has been dark for three years. The building needs two hundred thousand dollars in repairs. Mayor Hatch's development will bring jobs and tax revenue to Millhaven, and I think —
@LUNA
(standing)
Oscar.
@OSCAR
Luna, don't —
@LUNA
You didn't tell me.

The room goes quiet.

@OSCAR
Sit down.
@LUNA
You knew, and you didn't tell me.

She walks out. Oscar watches her go. He doesn't follow.

[Opening]
@FELIX
~I don't want to be here, I don't want to be here
~It's dark and it is cold and there are sounds
~Luna, what is that I hear, did something move just there
~Are there animals in old observatories?

@LUNA
~Felix.
@FELIX
~Are there?

[Verse]
@LUNA
~It's probably a pipe
@FELIX
~A pipe
@LUNA
~A heating pipe that's old
@FELIX
~That's old
@LUNA
~It's probably just drafts
@FELIX
~Just drafts
@LUNA
~It's forty years of cold

[Chorus]
@FELIX
~Dark dark dark dark dark
~Is the only word I know right now
~Dark dark dark dark dark
~How do you do this? How?

@LUNA
~Felix, you can see the stars from here

@FELIX
~I can't see anything from here!

@LUNA
~Give your eyes a minute

@FELIX
~My eyes have had a minute
~Can we please just go home

[Bridge]
@LUNA
~Look up.

(a long beat)

@FELIX
(quietly)
~Oh.

@LUNA
~Yeah.

@FELIX
~That's... that's a lot of stars.

@LUNA
~Wait till the telescope's working.

Luna carefully threads the new alignment pin into the telescope mount. Her hands are steady. Felix holds a penlight, barely breathing.

@LUNA
Okay. Don't move.
@FELIX
I'm not moving.
@LUNA
Don't even breathe.
@FELIX
I have to breathe, Luna.
@LUNA
Just —

A soft click. Luna sits back.

@LUNA
There.

She swings the telescope upward. Finds a gap in the dome. Adjusts the focus ring. Then steps back and gestures to Felix.

@LUNA
Look.

Felix puts his eye to the lens. A long silence.

@FELIX
That's... a lot of stars.
@LUNA
Wait till I fix the lens.
@FELIX
I thought you said it was fixed.
@LUNA
That was the mount. The lens is next.
@FELIX
How many things are broken?
@LUNA
It's a forty-year-old telescope, Felix.

Felix pulls Oscar aside outside the observatory.

@FELIX
I need to tell you something and you can't tell Luna I told you.
@OSCAR
What?
@FELIX
Hatch paid you. To support the demolition.
@OSCAR
Where did you hear that.
@FELIX
I didn't hear it. I saw the transfer notification on your phone when you left it on the counter at my mom's diner.
@OSCAR
That's private.
@FELIX
Oscar. She's in there right now scanning star charts at midnight. She skipped school today. She thinks she's doing this for her dad.

Oscar says nothing.

@FELIX
You have to tell her.
@OSCAR
I will.
@FELIX
When?
@OSCAR
When I figure out how.
@FELIX
Figure it out fast.

[Verse 1]
@LUNA
~The comet's in the photograph
~It's real
~It's small and white and traveling fast
~It's real

@OSCAR
~Luna.
@LUNA
~It's real, Oscar.

[Chorus]
@LUNA & OSCAR
~What he left us is a sky full of questions
~What he left us is a lens and a light
~What he left us — Vale-Carter, they'll call it
~What he left us is alive tonight

[Bridge]
@OSCAR
~I'm sorry. About the money. About Hatch.
~I should have told you.
@LUNA
~You should have.
@OSCAR
~I'm going to fix it.
@LUNA
~How?
@OSCAR
~I don't know yet.
(beat)
~But I'm a Carter. We fix broken things.

@LUNA
(smiling)
~Yeah we do.
